title: For Sale:  Austrian Steyr M95 Straight Pull Rifle 8x56R
postcontent:
Up for sale is an Austrian M95 straight pull carbine. These started life as long rifles chambered in 8x50R, and served as the main rifle for the Austro-Hungarian Empire. After WW1 they were shortened to carbine length, chambered for the more powerful 8x56R round, and a side sling swivel was added to the stock. These carbines were used by Hungarian forces and rear line German forces in WW2.

This particular rifle is in very good condition. Metal looks about 70%; there are some old dings and wear in the stock. The bore has some roughness but is still mostly bright with good rifling. The numbers seem to be matching except the stock. It was made in 1918. One en bloc clip is included.

title: For Sale:  Whitney Model 1841 “Mississippi Rifle”, dated 1850
postcontent: #2085 Whitney Model 1841 “Mississippi Rifle”, dated 1850 (both barrel and lockplate), still in the original 54-caliber with the six groove barrel and having a VERY decent bore! These handsome rifles were made famous during the Mexican War with their use by the future president of the Confederate States, Jefferson Davis who commanded a small force in Mississippi. The Model 1841 was used by Davis’ troops in the Battle of Buena Vista which saw Davis drive a superior force of the Mexican army from the battle field. Thus, these accurate weapons gained the name, Mississippi Rifles and became well known for their far better accuracy than the smoothbored muskets of that era. This rifle is in MUCH better condition than most seen; it has fine smooth metal with excellent deep markings, a fine bore, and almost no pitting whatsoever, not even around the nipple. The wood is equally superior with just minor bumps and bruises and does still have two visible cartouches. It also still has the spare nipple in the patchbox and the nipple wrench, as well. The sling is an obvious reproduction but is the correct type. Definitely very good collection quality! VG++ to near Fine overall.

title: For Sale:  ****Exceptional &Rare Swedish Model 1881 Jarmann Rifle****
postcontent: Swedish Jarmann Model 1881 bolt action repeater chambered in 10.15x61R. Barrel is 32" barrel with an excellent bright strong bore. This 1883 dated trials rifle is in excellent overall condition with the finish retaining about 97% original blue that has light handling wear and is lightly flaking to brown with a few areas that have specks of very fine surface oxidation present. The steel buttplate shows the most wear with light oxidation and abrasions, most likely from spending a good portion of its life on a rack. The bolt assembly is in the white and has a light gray patina slowly spreading over its surface and mixing with a few lights spots of surface oxidation. The receiver and barrel markings are all crisp and all numbers are matching. The left side of the receiver and barrel are both marked "(crown)/C / J.P 1883 J.G." The wood has some light added finish but otherwise rates excellent having only a few light dings. The area under the action has a blank brass diamond held on with two screws, which most likely would have served as an ID plate had the rifle been adopted and issued. The rifle's features include an eight shot tubular magazine and magazine disconnect on the left side of the receiver. The forward sling swivel and cleaning rod are missing but the rifle otherwise is complete. Only about 1500 of these were manufactured, and were never adopted for service. The first 500 were the two-band variation, made for the Royal Life Guard, and the remaining 1000 were this three-band variation produced for the Navy. Many were destroyed by the Germans or sold as surplus and/or converted to the M28 Harpoon rifle.
